<h2 id="20march1997">Update 1106G # Date 20 March 1997</h2>
<p>Chapter 1 - GENERAL PROCEDURES inc.TAX FILE NUMBER EXEMPTIONS - Death review. See guidelines 1.20600 to 1.20605.</p>
<p>The circumstances of a surviving partner must be reviewed to ascertain if overseas pension payments were being received by either or both or the couple, whether the survivor's entitlement change.</p>
<p>Where a surviving partner is a women aged 50 or over, with no recent workforce experience, then her eligibility for widow allowance should be explored. A claim for widow allowance should be invited where appropriate.</p>
<p>Where a surviving partner is a woman of age pension age who was not residentially qualified for an age pension, then her eligibility for an age pension under subsection 43(1A) of the Act should be explored. from 20 March 1997 a woman can qualify for an age pension if:</p>
<p>(a) the woman has reached age pension age; and</p>
<p>(b) the woman's partner has died; and</p>
<p>(c) both the woman and her partner were Australian residents when her partner died; and</p>
<p>(d) the woman was an Australian resident for a continuous period of at least 104 weeks immediately before the day she lodged the claim for the age pension.</p>
<p>If a survivor meets the criteria above she should be invited to claim age pension. If she already receives age pension paid under an agreement but her rate is reduced due to direct deductions of overseas pension, she can reclaim to qualify for a higher rate of pension.</p>
