<h2 id="6february1997">Update 816G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 47 - DROUGHT RELIEF PAYMENTS - Change to recovery period and revocations of drought relief payment. See guidelines 47.9000 to 47.10004.</p>
<p>(1) The change explains that recovery period has been extended from six months to twelve months.</p>
<p>(2) The change updates details of the revocation announced 31 December 1996.</p>
<h2>Update 815G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 47 - DROUGHT RELIEF PAYMENTS - Declarations of drought relief payment (DRP). See guidelines 47.2000 to 47.2013.</p>
<p>The change updates the number of declarations of drought since drought relief payment (DRP) was introduced.</p>
<h2>Update 814G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 38 - CHILD SUPPORT - Cosmetic change only. See guideline 38.2556.</p>
<h2>Update 813G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 38 - CHILD SUPPORT - Additional on-line advice available. See guideline 38.2450.</p>
<p>Description of new on-line advice to be issued to customers when the Child Support Agency advises an application for child support assessment has not been accepted plus correction to description for Q025.</p>
<h2>Update 812G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 45 - YOUTH TRAINING ALLOWANCE - Parental income test/parental assets test - parent overseas. See guidelines 45.21010 to 45.21303.</p>
<p>Abolish the minimum rate of NSA/YTA/SA/SpB for dependent recipients under 18 years of age. The parental means test will now be applied to the full rate of payment, tapering the rate until entitlement is nil. Date of effect is 1 January 1997.</p>
<h2>Update 811G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 45 - YOUTH TRAINING ALLOWANCE - Industrial action deferment period. See guidelines 45.1180 to 45.1183.</p>
<p>This amendment outlines the entitlement to Special Benefit of customers who are subjected to a six week deferment period as a result of taking industrial action that was in breach of an order, direction or injunction by a State authority, the Industrial Relations Commission or the Federal Court, which has resulted in their unemployment.</p>
<h2>Update 810G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 15 - SPECIAL BENEFIT - Industrial action deferment period. See guidelines 15.3500 to 15.3502.</p>
<p>This amendment outlines the entitlement to special benefit of customers who are subjected to a six week deferment period as a result of taking industrial action that was in breach of an order, direction or injunction by a State authority, the Industrial Relations Commission or the Federal Court, which has resulted in their unemployment.</p>
<h2>Update 809G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Newstart allowance - reclaiming. See guidelines 12.13900 to 12.15054 (deleted for release 4.77 11/12/97).</p>
<p>This amendment is to update policy on reclaiming and signature check exercised on Form SU19.</p>
<h2>Update 808G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Newstart allowance - other activities that may satisfy the activity test. See guidelines 12.2500 to 12.2553.</p>
<p>This amendment is to remove youth training allowance references from the newstart chapter.</p>
<h2>Update 807G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Newstart allowance - continuation form - Form SU19. See guidelines 12.16100 to 12.16505.</p>
<p>This amendment is to update the policy relating to continuation form - Form SU19.</p>
<h2>Update 806G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 42 - PORTABILITY AND COMPARABLE FOREIGN PAYMENTS - Comparable foreign payment and foreign pension claim procedures. See guidelines 42.2330 to 42.2331.</p>
<p>Provides a contact address for people wishing to follow up on pension entitlements from South Africa.</p>
<h2>Update 805G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 44 - INDEPENDENT RATE - Assessment of claims. See guidelines 44.4420 to 44.4422.</p>
<p>Abolish the minimum rate of NSA/YTA/SA/SpB for dependent recipients under 18 years of age. The parental means test will now be applied to the full rate of payment, tapering the rate until entitlement is nil. Date of effect is 1 January 1997.</p>
<h2>Update 803G to 804G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 43 - PARTNER ALLOWANCE - Industrial action deferment period. See guidelines 43.100 and 43.240 to 43.243.</p>
<p>This amendment outlines the entitlement to partner allowance of customers who are subjected to a six week deferment period as a result of taking industrial action that was in breach of an order, direction or injunction by a State authority, the Industrial Relations Commission or the Federal Court, which has resulted in their unemployment.</p>
<h2>Update 802G # Date 6 February 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 4 - COMPENSATION FOR DEFECTIVE ADMINISTRATION - Referral of compensation for detriment caused by defective administration (CDDA) and act of grace claims to National Administration. See guidelines 4.17100 to 4.17102.</p>
<p>This policy has now been changed to require that the above submissions are to be forwarded to the FAS of the relevant policy Division. The rationale for this change is that both CDDA and act of grace payments are 'ex gratia' type payments that allow the Department to compensate even though there is no legal liability to pay. That is, it is generally a policy decision as to whether it is appropriate to recommend compensation under either of these discretionary payments.</p>
<h2 id="23january1997">Update 801G # Date 23 January 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART ALLOWANCE - (1) Newstart/youth training allowance reviews. (2) Part P: Selective Reviews - Part Q: Incapacity Reviews. See guidelines 12.18000 to 12.21903.</p>
<p>(1) This amendment is to update the policy on the customer selection method for 12 week (DC), nine month (DE) and 10% intensive (DP) entitlement reviews and the procedure for conducting these reviews. As part of the new guidelines, annual reviews are no longer conducted.</p>
<p>(2) Newstart allowance to replace jobsearch allowance.</p>
<h2>Update 800G # Date 23 January 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART ALLOWANCE - (1) Activity Test: Increase in deferment period for moving to an area of lower employment to 26 weeks. (2) Industrial action deferment period. See guidelines 12.8500 to 12.8502 and 12.8600 to 12.8603.</p>
<p>(1) With this amendment, legislative changes which commence 1 January 1997 increase the deferment period applicable to a customer who reduces their employment prospects by moving to an area of lower employment without DEETYA approval. The period is increased from 12 to 26 weeks.</p>
<p>(2) This amendment introduces a six (6) week deferment period for customers who have undertaken industrial action that was in breach of an order, direction or injunction issued by a State authority, the Industrial Relations Commission or the Federal Court, which has resulted in their unemployment.</p>
<h2>Update 799G # Date 23 January 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART ALLOWANCE - Industrial action deferment period. See guidelines 12.1030 to 12.1073.</p>
<p>This amendment introduces a six (6) week deferment period for customers who have undertaken industrial action that was in breach of an order, direction or injunction issued by a State authority, the Industrial Relations Commission or the Federal Court, which has resulted in their unemployment.</p>
<h2>Update 798G # Date 23 January 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 45 - YOUTH TRAINING ALLOWANCE - Industrial action deferment period. See guidelines 45.1130 to 45.1141.</p>
<p>This amendment introduces a six (6) week deferment period for customers who have undertaken industrial action that was in breach of an order, direction or injunction issued by a State authority, the Industrial Relations Commission or the Federal Court, which has resulted in their unemployment.</p>
<h2>Update 797G # Date 23 January 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 12 - NEWSTART - Procedures for monitoring job search activities. See guidelines 12.2800 to 12.3005.</p>
<p>This amendment updates the policy guidelines relating to the issue and return of Jobseeker Diary and Employer Contact Certificates and customers providing full employer details on SU19s. Legislation has been amended to increase the non payment period for customers moving to an Area of low employment prospects from 13 to 26 weeks. This has a date of effect of 1 January 1997.</p>
<h2>Update 796G # Date 23 January 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 45 - YOUTH TRAINING ALLOWANCE - 1) Activity test: increase in deferment period for moving to an area of lower employment to 26 weeks -YTA. 2) Industrial action deferment period. See guidelines 45.8500 to 45.8502 and 45.8600 to 45.8700.</p>
<p>1) With this amendment, and proposed legislative changes in March 1997, the onus has been placed on the customer to show the delegate that sufficient reason exits for their voluntary unemployment or refusal of a job offer. The requirements will remove some of the discretion which now exists which will result in more consistent decisions across the network.</p>
<p>2) This amendment introduces a six (6) week deferment period for customers who have undertaken industrial action that was in breach of an order, direction or injunction issued by a State authority, the Industrial Relations Commission or the Federal Court, which has resulted in their unemployment.</p>
<h2>Update 795G # Date 23 January 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 42 - PORTABILITY AND COMPARABLE FOREIGN PAYMENTS - Changing pension types while overseas - agreement pensioners See guidelines 42.1170 to42.1172.</p>
<p>The new guidelines amplify and consolidate current guideline 42.1170.</p>
<h2 id="9january1997">Update 794G # Date 9 January 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 38 - CHILD SUPPORT - Transferring applications for child support assessment immediately to the Child Support Agency. See guidelines 38.4000 to 38.4355.</p>
<p>To reflect changes to work practices indicated in National Instruction CB960190.</p>
<h2>Update 793G # Date 9 January 1997</h2>
<p>CHAPTER 38 - CHILD SUPPORT - Transferring applications for child support assessment immediately to the Child Support Agency. See guidelines 38.1300 to 38.1321.</p>
<p>To reflect changes to work practices as indicated in National Instruction CB960190.</p>
